04645nam a22007455i 9780812202441DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20151996pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122024417 a10.9783/97808122024412doi  a(DE-B1597)451225  a(OCoLC)979778771  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aLIT0041502bisacsh04a700/.944/090332201 aKavanagh, Thomas M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEsthetics of the Moment :bLiterature and Art in the French Enlightenment /cThomas M. Kavanagh. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2015] 4cÂ©1996  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b51 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCritical Authors and Issues00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Versions of the Moment -- t2. Lahontan and the Moment Between Cultures -- t3. Diderot and the Epicurean Moment -- t4. Graffigny's Epiphany of the Moment -- t5. Rousseau's Moment Beyond History -- t6 Casanova and the Moment of Chance -- t7. Roger de Piles and the Moment's Glance -- t8. Du Bos, Poussin, and the Force of the Moment -- t9. Watteau's Incarnate Moment -- t10. Chardin and the Moment Beyond Nature -- t11. Boucher, Fragonard, and the Seductions of the Moment -- t12. Greuze and the Moment Foreclosed -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe literature and art of the French Enlightenment is everywhere marked by an intense awareness of the moment. The parallel projects of living in, representing, and learning from the moment run through the Enlightenment's endeavors as tokens of an ambition and a heritage imposing its only and ultimately impossible cohesion. In this illuminating study, Thomas M. Kavanagh argues that Enlightenment culture and its tensions, contradictions, and achievements flow from a subversive attention to the present as present, freed from the weight of past and future.Examining a wide sweep of literary and artistic culture, Kavanagh argues against the traditional view of the Age of Reason as one of coherent, recognizable ideology expressed in a structured narrative form. In literature, he analyzes the moment at work in the inebriating lightness of Marivaux's repartee; the new-found freedom of Lahontan's and Rousseau's ideals of a consciousness limited to the present; Diderot's championing of Epicurean epistemology; Graffigny's portrayal of abrupt cultural displacement; and Casanova's penchant for chance's redefining moment. The moment in art theory and practice is explored in such forms as de Piles's defense of color; Du Bos's foregrounding of perception; Watteau's indulgence in a corporeal present; Chardin's dismantling of mimesis; and Boucher's and Fragonard's thematics of desire.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aArts, French. 0aArts, Moderny18th century. 0aUt pictura poesis (Aesthetics). 4aArchitecture. 4aCultural Studies. 4aFine Art. 4aFine Arts. 4aGarden History. 4aLiterature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / French.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn eBook Package Archive 1898-1999 (pre Pub)z978311044252640uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081220244140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812202441423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812202441.jpg  a978-3-11-044252-6  Penn eBook Package Archive 1898-1999c1898d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK